verbs.description: reschedule (third-person singular simple present reschedules, present participle rescheduling, simple past and past participle rescheduled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To schedule again or at a different time.
examples: We'll have to reschedule next Monday's meeting because of the public holiday.

entries.meaning: (transitive, US, law) To reclassify; to change the schedule (division into which something is classified) of.
examples: Moreover, marijuana could only be brought to market if it were rescheduled to acknowledge its “accepted medical use,” according to DEA standards.
